        <svcproc svcproctype="repair" graphiccount="9">
            <title>SERVICE PROCEDURE</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove front and rear snap-on column covers (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9205011">Figure 1</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f9205011" figsize="pg-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9205011.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 1. Front And Rear Snap-On Covers</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tilt column to its lowest position.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the turn signal switch.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Push cancellation cam (plastic sleeve) firmly against the upper bearing (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9205012">Figure 2</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f9205012" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9205012.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 2. Cancellation Cam</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. BEARING</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. CANCELLATION CAM</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Make a mark approximately 1/2 inch from the shoulder end of the cancellation cam and
                    between two lobes of the cam (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9205013">Figure 3</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f9205013" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9205013.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 3. Mark On Cam</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">On the CHIP SHEET (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9205019">Figure 9</hotlnk>) cut out the square as illustrated. The chip guard is to
                    insure that the chips created by drilling the shaft DO NOT fall into the bearings (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9205014">Figure 4</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>Making sure that no chips fall into the bearings is a very important step.</para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>Failure to adhere to step 6 can result in damage to the shaft bearings.</para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f9205014" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9205014.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 4. Chip Guard</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">To install the chip guard (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9205019">Figure 9</hotlnk>), tape the paper to the sleeve so the mark on the
                    cancellation sleeve is exposed through the center of the square (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9205015">Figure 5</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f9205015" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9205015.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 5. Chip Guard Installed</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. TAPE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. MARK ON CANCELLATION CAM</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. CHIP GUARD</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With the drill provided in the kit, drill a hole located at the mark on the cancellation
                    cam. Drill through the cancellation cam and into the steering shaft. Drill the hole 1/4 inch deep
                    into the steering shaft (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9205016">Figure 6</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f9205016" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9205016.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 6. Drilling Hole</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. PLASTIC SLEEVE</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. STEERING SHAFT</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Insert the drive screw into the drilled hole. With a hammer, drive the drive screw
                    through the cancellation cam and into the steering shaft until the head of the drive screw is firmly
                    seated against the cancellation cam (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9205017">Figure 7</hotlnk>and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9205018">Figure 8</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f9205017" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9205017.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 7. Installing Drive Screw</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f9205018" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9205018.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 8. Drive Screw Installed</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the turn signal switch and verify that the wire routing is the same as it
                    originally was.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Start engine and make sure turn signal cancels properly in both directions. Also, make
                    sure that the drive screw does not hit any part of the steering column while making the turns.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install snap on front and rear column covers.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Test drive the vehicle to be sure no irregularities exist in the turn signal or
                    steering.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f9205019" figsize="full-pg">
                <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9205019.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 9. Chip Guard</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcproc>
